<subSubSection pageId="64" pageNumber="65" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="64.[151,1436,1649,1998]" pageId="64" pageNumber="65">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,273,1685,1710]" pageId="64" pageNumber="65">Notes.</emphasis>
This is a cleptoparasite of multiple 
<taxonomicName box="[676,782,1686,1709]" class="Insecta" family="Melittidae" genus="Macropis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="64" pageNumber="65" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[676,782,1686,1709]" italics="true" pageId="64" pageNumber="65">Macropis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species likely including 
<taxonomicName authority="(Cockerell)" authorityName="Cockerell" box="[1061,1290,1685,1710]" class="Insecta" family="Andrenidae" genus="Andrena" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="64" pageNumber="65" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nuda">
<emphasis box="[1061,1084,1686,1709]" italics="true" pageId="64" pageNumber="65">M</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[1099,1155,1685,1710]" italics="true" pageId="64" pageNumber="65">nuda</emphasis>
(Cockerell)
</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Sheffield" etAl="et al." firstAuthor="Sheffield" pageId="64" pageNumber="65" pagination="161 - 164" refId="ref102585" refString="Sheffield, C. S., Rigby, S. M., Smith, R. F. &amp; Kevan, P. G. (2004) The rare cleptoparasitic bee Epeoloides pilosula (Hymenoptera: Apoidea: Apidae) discovered in Nova Scotia, Canada, with distributional notes. Journal of the Kansas Entomological Society, 77, 161 - 164. https: // doi. org / 10.2317 / 0310.23.1" type="journal article" year="2004">
<collectingRegion box="[1304,1408,1685,1710]" country="United Kingdom" name="Sheffield" pageId="64" pageNumber="65">Sheffield</collectingRegion>
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="64" pageNumber="65">et al.</emphasis>
2004
</bibRefCitation>
) and 
<taxonomicName authority="Patton (Wagner &amp; Ascher 2008)" authorityName="Patton (Wagner &amp; Ascher" authorityYear="2008" box="[304,781,1721,1746]" class="Insecta" family="Melittidae" genus="Macropis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="64" pageNumber="65" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ciliata">
<emphasis box="[304,327,1722,1745]" italics="true" pageId="64" pageNumber="65">M</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[341,412,1721,1746]" italics="true" pageId="64" pageNumber="65">ciliata</emphasis>
Patton (
<bibRefCitation author="Wagner &amp; Ascher" box="[504,773,1721,1746]" firstAuthor="Wagner" pageId="64" pageNumber="65" pagination="81 - 83" refId="ref105371" refString="Wagner, D. L. &amp; Ascher, J. S. (2008) Rediscovery of Epeoloides pilosula (Hymenoptera: Apoidea: Apidae) in New England. Journal of the Kansas Entomological Society, 81, 81 - 83. http: // doi. org / 10.2317 / JKES- 703.19.1" type="journal article" year="2008">Wagner &amp; Ascher 2008</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
, which in turn are specialists on 
<taxonomicName box="[1142,1270,1721,1746]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Primulaceae" genus="Lysimachia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Ericales" pageId="64" pageNumber="65" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1142,1270,1721,1746]" italics="true" pageId="64" pageNumber="65">Lysimachia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<taxonomicName box="[1284,1432,1721,1746]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Myrsinaceae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" order="Ericales" pageId="64" pageNumber="65" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Myrsinaceae</taxonomicName>
, formerly 
<taxonomicName box="[260,401,1757,1782]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Primulaceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Ericales" pageId="64" pageNumber="65" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Primulaceae</taxonomicName>
) (
<bibRefCitation author="Cane" box="[428,631,1757,1782]" etAl="et al." firstAuthor="Cane" pageId="64" pageNumber="65" pagination="257 - 264" refId="ref85108" refString="Cane, J. H., Eickwort, G. C., Wesley, F. R. &amp; Spielholz, J. (1983) Foraging, grooming and mate-seeking behaviors of Macropis nuda (Hymenoptera, Melittidae) and use of Lysimachia ciliata (Primulaceae) oils in larval provisions and cell linings. American Midland Naturalist, 110, 257 - 264. https: // doi. org / 10.2307 / 2425267" type="journal article" year="1983">
Cane 
<emphasis box="[499,560,1757,1782]" italics="true" pageId="64" pageNumber="65">et al.</emphasis>
1983
</bibRefCitation>
). Observations were lacking from its entire range for many decades (
<bibRefCitation author="Michener" box="[158,337,1793,1818]" firstAuthor="Michener" pageId="64" pageNumber="65" refId="ref95307" refString="Michener, C. D. (2000) The bees of the world. The Johns Hopkins University Press, Baltimore, 913 pp." type="book" year="2000">Michener 2000</bibRefCitation>
), but it has been rediscovered very locally in 
<collectingCountry box="[873,957,1793,1818]" name="Canada" pageId="64" pageNumber="65">Canada</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Sheffield" box="[974,1215,1793,1818]" etAl="et al." firstAuthor="Sheffield" pageId="64" pageNumber="65" pagination="161 - 164" refId="ref102585" refString="Sheffield, C. S., Rigby, S. M., Smith, R. F. &amp; Kevan, P. G. (2004) The rare cleptoparasitic bee Epeoloides pilosula (Hymenoptera: Apoidea: Apidae) discovered in Nova Scotia, Canada, with distributional notes. Journal of the Kansas Entomological Society, 77, 161 - 164. https: // doi. org / 10.2317 / 0310.23.1" type="journal article" year="2004">
<collectingRegion box="[974,1078,1793,1818]" country="United Kingdom" name="Sheffield" pageId="64" pageNumber="65">Sheffield</collectingRegion>
<emphasis box="[1088,1148,1793,1818]" italics="true" pageId="64" pageNumber="65">et al.</emphasis>
2004
</bibRefCitation>
) and in the 
<collectingCountry name="United States of America" pageId="64" pageNumber="65">United States</collectingCountry>
in New 
<collectingCountry box="[320,413,1829,1854]" name="United Kingdom" pageId="64" pageNumber="65">England</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Wagner &amp; Ascher" box="[430,706,1829,1854]" firstAuthor="Wagner" pageId="64" pageNumber="65" pagination="81 - 83" refId="ref105371" refString="Wagner, D. L. &amp; Ascher, J. S. (2008) Rediscovery of Epeoloides pilosula (Hymenoptera: Apoidea: Apidae) in New England. Journal of the Kansas Entomological Society, 81, 81 - 83. http: // doi. org / 10.2317 / JKES- 703.19.1" type="journal article" year="2008">Wagner &amp; Ascher 2008</bibRefCitation>
) and 
<collectingRegion box="[773,890,1829,1854]" country="United States of America" name="New York" pageId="64" pageNumber="65">
New 
<collectingRegion box="[835,890,1829,1854]" country="United Kingdom" name="York" pageId="64" pageNumber="65">York</collectingRegion>
</collectingRegion>
(http://bugguide.net/node/view/954741). Of the four specimens examined from 
<collectingRegion box="[505,615,1865,1890]" country="United States of America" name="Michigan" pageId="64" pageNumber="65">Michigan</collectingRegion>
, none was collected in the last 70 years.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
